THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE UNAFFECTED CANS WERE REPACKAGED, AND WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS AS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED AN INVESTIGATION USING LEVEL B PROTECTION.  UPON FURTHER  INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM TWO, ONE THOUSAND POUND CYLINDERS. APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF A GAS WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE VALVES ON THE CYLINDERS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM TIGHTENED THE VALVES ON THE CYLINDERS AND THEY WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING NINE, ONE QUART BOTTLES WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER EIGHT WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLE WAS DUE TO TOP HEAVY FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND ALL NINE BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS AS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, 6 WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING 6, ONE QUART BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 25 BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED AND 11 WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTONS WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON CARDBOARD RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DUNNAGE WAS PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THE ELEVEN UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE REPACKAGED AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO OTHER FREIGHT WAS AFFECTED.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF TRAILER #6576, OUR PROCESSING PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED A RELEASE OF LIQUID FROM AN UPRIGHT BOX.  THE BOX WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN A PLASTIC DRUM.  THE AREA, ON WHICH THE RELEASE OCCURRED, WAS DECONTAMINATED.  TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THE SAME INCIDENT, WE WILL REVIEW THE REQUIRED PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS WITH THE SHIPPER (GENERATOR/CUSTOMER).

UPON COMPLETION OF LOADING, SHIPPER PLACED A NITROGEN BLANKET ON TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT.  AT THAT POINT PRODUCT STARTED A VERY SLOW DRIP THRU THE TRAILER BELLY SKIN.  A BUCKET PLACED UNDER TRAILER TO CONTAIN TRANSFERRED FOR DELIVERY.  TRAILER WITH LEAK CLEANED AND TAKEN TO REPAIR FACILITY FOR CORRECTIVE REPAIRS.

DURING TRANSPORTATION A SKID OF METAL RUBBED AGAINST THIS SHIPMENT CAUSING A HOLE AND MINOR LEAKAGE.  THE DAMAGE BAG WAS REMOVED FROM SKID AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS TO BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AND DISPOSAL.
WHILE THE DRUM WAS SITTING ON OUR DOCK WE NOTICED A SMALL STRESS LEAK ON THE BOTTOM RIM.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER WITHOUT ANY FURTHER PROBLEMS.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD DOOR 7 AT 23:50 PM WEARING PULL P.P.E.  I FOUND A 5 PART HAZMAT WITH A STAIN ONSIDES AND BOTTOM.  CONSULTED DESISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL HUB AND REMOVED TO HAZMAT RE-WRAP AREA.  INSPECTION SHOWED THAT THE CAP ON 5GAL CONTAINER WAS LEAKING.  PRODUCT WAS REPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER, WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.  I DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT MEAD PAPER.  HE HOOKED UP THE HOSE TO THE TRAILER AND BEGAN THE PRODUCT FLOW.  THERE WAS A SLIGHT DRIP AROUND THE 3" FITTING ON THE HOSE.  THE DRIVER REPLACED THE GASKET AND HOOKED IT BACK UP AND HAD TO KEEP MESSING WITH IT.  HE FINALLY WAS ABLE TO CONTROL THE DRIP.  THE DRIVER WALKED OVER TO TELL THE UNLOADER THAT THE FITTING ON THE HOSE NEEDED TO BE REPLACED.  THE HOSE WAS A BRAND NEW ONE THAT MEAD PAPER HAD MADE.  THE DRIVER WAS WALKING OUT OF THE UNLOADING OFFICE WHEN THE HOSE RIPPED OFF OF THE FITTING CAUSING CAUSTIC TO SPILL OUT OF THE BACK VALVE ONTO THE GROUND.  THE BAND CLAMPS ON THE HOSE FAILED TO HOLD.  THERE WAS A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 1,140 GALLONS.

column168: REAGENT CHEMICAL TANK TRUCK WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF HCL 20 BE. TANK TRUCK WAS ALMOST EMPTY SO THE DRIVER, JOHN ALLEN , WAS ON TOP OF THE TANKER READY TO CUT OFF OUR SUPPLY & VALVE.  WHEN THE HOSE STARTED TO MOVE AROUND (INDICATING TANKER EMPTY) AN ELBOW ON THE FILL LINE TO THE STORAGE TANK BROKE & DROPPED SOWN (ACTUALLY THE BRACE THAT HELD THE FILL LINE UP HAD RUSTED AWAY AND BROKEN).  A MINUTE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN MIST FORM CAME OUT OF THE BROKEN FILL LINE, SPRAYING THE DRIVER (HE WAS WEARING RAINSUIT, GOGGLES, FACESHIELD, GLOVES.  THE DRIVER CUT OFF THE AIR, MADE SURE NO HCL ON SKIN & DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM VALVES.

ON MARCH 5,2000 CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT LEEWOOD YARD IN MEMPHIS TN FOUND QOTX 266 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. PERSONNEL FROM PENN SPECIALTY CHEMICALS RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND SUMMONED A CONTRACTOR TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE AND CLEANUP COMPLETED.

INBOUND CAR INSPECTOR NOTICE AN ODOR FROM THIS CAR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD. THE DUST FLAP ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS IN THE UP POSITION AND IT WAS DEDUCED THAT THE PRODUCT RELIEF VALVE HAD FUNCTIONED. A SLIGHT ODOR WAS NOTICEABLE AROUND THE CAR. THE SHIPPER AND CSXT REPRESENTATIVE FURTHER ASSESSED THE CAR AND WERE ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE 20 NUTS ON THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE NUTS THAT SECURED THE 2 VAPOR VALVES 2 LIQUID VALVES AND THE PRODUCT RELIEF VALVE. THE PACKING ON THE LEFT VAPOR VALVE ALSO HAD TO BE ADJUSTED DUE TO A VAPOR LEAK. THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 290 PSIG. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR A TRUCK LOAD OF MATERIALS TO BE TRANSFERRED OFF THE CAR. THE PRESSURE DROPPED TO 30 PSIG (NORMAL SHIPPING RANGE) AFTER 32000 LBS. OF PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED INTO THE TRUCK.

column168: 40/50 LB BAGS ON PALLET SHRINK WRAPPED WITH DOUBLE PALLET ON BOTTOM. BAG ON BOTTOM BURST DUE TO WEIGHT OF OTHER PRODUCT ON TOP.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DAMAGED THIRTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE CAUSE OF DAMAGE TO THE DRUM COULD NOT BE DETERMINED.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, Inc OF GUTHRIE, OKLAHOMA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON METAL OVER PACK DRUM.  THE OVER PACK DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: WHLE UNLOADING, ONE 10 POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS DAMAGED ON THE DOCK. APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGED TO THE CYLINDER WAS CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT DAMAGING A VALVE ON TOP OF THE CYLINDER.  THE FREE PRODUCT EVAPORATED AS IT WAS RELEASED AND DID NOT REQUIRE CLEAN UP.  THE CYLINDER WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK A WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-GALLON CANS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS, Inc TERMINAL IN DENVER, COLORADO WITH THE WET CARTON.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE CANS WAS LEAKING, AND THREE OF THE CANS WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY SIX OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE CAN WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE LID. THE ADAM COUNTY, COLORADO FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE TERMINAL TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. THE DAMAGED CAN, AFFECTED CANS, REMAINING PRODUCT. WET CARTON, AFFECTED DUNNAGE AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER'S DISPOSITION. column168: I RESPONDED TO THE ABOVE LOCATION TO INVESTIGATE THE TRANSFER RELEASE THAt OCCURRED WHILE COUNTRY LINES DRIVER ROBERT LEE FAULCON WAS MAKING A DELIVERY.  UPON ARRIVAL I SPOKE TO MR. VINCENT LYNCH, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, FOR PERDUE FARMS.  PERDUE HAD ORDERED 2000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FOR THE FEED MILL PLANT.  WHEN THE COUNTRY LINES TANKER TRUCK ARRIVED MR. FAULCON NOTED THAT THE GAUGE ON TOP OF THE TANK READ 5'3".  THIS IS AN 8' DIAMETER TANK AND THE READING MR. FAULCON GOT WOULD INDICATE THAT THE TANK CONTAINED 3488 GALLONS OF FUEL.  MR. FAULCON DID NOT GAUGE THE TANK PRIOR TO OFF LOADING BECAUSE HE THOUGHT THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM FOR THE 2000 GALLONS OF FUEL.  WHILE OFF LOADING MR. FAULCON STATED THAT HE OBSERVED FUEL COMING FROM THE VENT PIPE.  OBSERVATIONS ON SITE ALSO INDICATE THAT FUEL ESCAPED FROM THE MANWAYS ALSO.  THE AMOUNT OF FUEL THAT WAS SPILT APPEARS TO BE ABOUT 60-75 GALLONS.  MR. FAULCON IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE FUEL FLOW WHEN HE OBSERVED THE OVER FILL.  A&A ENVIRONMENTAL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  I SPOKE TO MR. FRANK MATTHEW, A&A SUPERVISOR AND HE STATED THE CONTAMINATES SOIL WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A LICENSED RECYCLING FACILITY.  THIS ADMINISTRATION WILL REQUIRE A COPY OF DISPOSAL RECEIPTS.  I ALSO SPOKE TO DONALD PUSEY, PLANT MANAGER OF THE FEED MILL, AND HE STATED THAT HE WAS NOT AWARE THE FUEL WAS ORDERED UNTIL THE OVERFILL OCCURRED.  MR. FAULCON DID NOT HAVE A TANK CHART IN HIS VEHICLE SO MR. PUSEY PROVIDED HIM WITH A COPY.  MR FAULCON WAS INSTRUCTED THAT THE TANK MUST BE GAUGED PRIOR TO OFF LOADING TO ENSURE AN INCIDENT OF THIS NATURE DOES NOT OCCUR AGAIN.  MR. LYNCH ALSO STATED THAT THE GAUGE INDICATING FEET CHANGED TO ONE THAT READS GALLONS.  WHILE ON SITE FUEL CONTINUED TO LEAK FRO MANWAYS DUE TO EXPANSION.  A&A WAS ADVISED TO PUMP SOME FUEL FROM THE TANK.

HE INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT AND CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER.  PACKAGE WAS HELD PER FAA INSTRUCTIONS SO THAT A TEST SAMPLE COULD DETERMINE THE TRUE FLASHPOINT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: IBC WAS LOADED ON THE TRAILER FOR FOR TRANSPORT.  INVESTIGATION CONCLUDES THAT THE VEHICLE VIBRATION CAUSED THE DISCHARGE VALVE ASSEMBLY, WHICH APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN LOOSE, TO LOOSEN EVEN MORE.  AS THE ASSEMBLY LOOSENED AND TWISTED, THE BALL VALVE HANDLE WAS FORCED AGAINST THE FRAME CAUSING IT TO OPEN SLIGHTY  PRODUCING THE SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE WHEN HE NOTICED THE FUMES COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  AFTER INSPECTION HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR.  HE RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN.  WE FOUND THAT THE MAJORITY OF PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE IBC WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFER TO ANOTHER IBC AND MEASURED TO DETERMINE THE 25-GALLON RELEASE.  THE MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH A NEUTRALIZING ABSORBENT, THE TRAILER WAS WASHED IN CONTAINMENT AND THE WATER WAS NEUTRALIZED ACCORDING TO PERMIT.  POST ACCIDENT TEST FOUND THE VALVE DID NOT MALFUNCTION NOR DAMAGED, BUT THE WHOLE ASSEMBLY WAS LOOSE, REPAIRED AND TESTED WITH  WATER.

ONE OF THE BAGS ON THE PALLET HAD SAGGED BETWEEN THE SLATS OF THE PALLET.  THE BAG HAD SETTLED FAR ENOUGH THROUGH THE SLATS THAT WHEN THE FORK LIFT BLADES WERE INSERTED INTO THE PALLET THE FORK LIFT BLADE RIPPED THE BAG.  CONTENTS OF THE BAG SPILLED BENEATH THE PALLET AND ON TO THE THE TRAILER FLOOR.  SPILLED CONTENTS WERE SEPT UP AND PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE OPEN BAG.  DRUM AS RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  RECOMMEND SHIPPING ON PALLETS WITH SLATS CLOSER TOGETHER OR PUTTING A SLIP SHEET BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE BAGS.

THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE FALLEN TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED BY COMPANY PERSONNEL IN TO THE REPLACEMENT TRAILER WITH NO ADDITIONAL PRODUCT LOSS.  TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF OCCURRENCE IN THE FUTURE, COMPANY POLICY REQUIRES THAT LOADED TRAILERS MAY ONLY BE SPOTTED  AT OFF TERMINAL LOCATIONS WITH PRIOR COMPANY APPROVAL.  NO TRAILERS ARE TO BE SPOTTED ON A SURFACE OTHER THAN CONCRETE WITHOUT ADDITIONAL MEANS OF SUPPORTING THE TRAILER AND THE LOAD.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIVE-GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TOP OF THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS SECURED AND THE PAIL WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHEN TERMINAL PERSONNEL OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS TO BEGIN UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON CONTAINERS FELL OUT ONTO THE DOCK.  THREE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO FREIGHT BEING LOADED IMPROPERLY.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, A BOOM, ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, THREE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND ONE WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE UNAFFECTED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A RECOUP DRUM AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A TRAILER LEAKING WHEN COMING INTO THE TERMINAL. FOUR DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON PAILS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE ASPHALT AND FOUR GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED IN THE TRAILER.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAILS WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND ONE EMPTY PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE  HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE OTHER DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO ANOTHER THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, THIRTY GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTY GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, FOUR WET CARTONS CONTAINING TWO, 2.5- GALLON BOTTLES EACH WERE DISCOVERED IN THE THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS DAMAGED,  ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS AFFECTED, AND SIX OF THE BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE BOTTLE WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE DAMAGED BOTTLE, REMAINING PRODUCT, WET CARTONS, ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55- GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE PLASTIC DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE AFFECTED BOTTLE WAS WIPED OFF, REPACKAGED, AND WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH UNAFFECTED BOTTLES AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED 2 1/2 GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PLASTIC PAIL WAS DUE TO IT BEING CRUSHED DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, PPE, AND DUNNAGE.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND THE DAMAGED 2 1/2 GALLON PLASTIC PAIL AND ITS REMAINING CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FRONT 1/4 MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGED TO THE STEEL DRUM WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM AND ITS REMAINING CONTENTS WERE CONTAINED AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIBERBOARD BOX, CONTAINING TWELVE, SIXTEEN OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS AFFECTED AND THE REMAINING ELEVEN RECEPTACLES WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INSIDE THE DAMAGED CARTON.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, THE FIBERBOARD BOX, AND THE ONE DAMAGED 16 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE AND ITS REMAINING CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED A VAPOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER THEN CAUGHT FIRE. APPROXIMATELY 396 POUNDS OF AN OXIDIZING SOLID, N.O.S. WERE DESTROYED.  THE PIEDMONT FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE PIEDMONT SHERRIF'S DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THERE WAS ALSO A MEDIA CREW THAT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PUT OUT THE FIRE AND 3R ENVIRONMENTAL OF GREER, SC WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THERE WERE 14 EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THEY ALL RECEIVED MEDICAL ATTENTION AND WERE RELEASED.  THERE WAS ALSO TWO RESIDENTS OF THE AREA THAT REPORTED FEELING SYMPTOMS OF ILLNESS DUE TO THE RELEASE, THEY DID NOT RECEIVE MEDICAL ATTENTION.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND ALL STATE LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

WHILE STAGED ON THE DOCK, A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A PATCH ON THE SIDE.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND AUTHORIZED RETURN.

column168: DURING A MORNING INSPECTION OF THE WAREHOUSE AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY  A SAFETY KLEEN  EMPLOYEE FOUND A 10 GALLON SPILL UNDERNEATH A 55 GALLON DRUM HAVING A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM SEAM DUE TO METAL FATIGUE. 3 SHIPMENTS WERE LOADED ONTO THE DYNAMEX TRUCK WHICH TAKES OUR FREIGHT TO TORONTO. THE DRIVER OF THE DYNAMEX TRUCK STARTED TO PULL AWAY FROM THE DOCK SO HE COULD CLOSE THE DOOR. HE FAILED TO LOWERS HIS ROLLERS  AND LD3 CONTAINER FELL OFF THE TRUCK TAKING SOME LOOSE FREIGHT WITH IT.  WE CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND THE LOCAL FAA AND FIRE AND POLICE. THE FIRE DEPT OPENED UP ONE CARTON FOUND ONE CARTON OF SKIN FIRMING TONING AGENT CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS (AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE SODIUM HYDROXIDE) CLASS 8 UN 1760 PACKING GROUP 11 LTD QTY PACKING  INSTY808. THE FIRE DEPT DEEMED EVERYTHING SAFE. WE HAD THE CARTONS REPACKED THE NEXT DAY AND FORWARDED TO FINAL DEST. NAME OF COMPANY THAT REPACKED: RESTRICTED ARTICLES SPECIALISTS BENSVILLE IL

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE COMING DOWN A HILL.  THE DRIVER RAN THE VEHICLE OFF OF THE ROAD INSTEAD OF REAR ENDING ANOTHER VEHICLE. AFTER THE VEHICLE RAN OFF OF THE ROAD, APPROXIMATELY 15 ADDITIONAL GALLONS WERE LOST DURING THE TRANSFER DUE TO THE TRANSFER TAKING PLACE ON A HILL.  LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO CALLED TO SECURE THE SCENE. THIS WAS A CASE OF DRIVER ERROR.  THE DRIVER WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING.

PICKED UP 4 LOOSE DRUMS AT CREST CHEM.  DROVE TO K.O. STEEL AND PICKED UP 5 BUNDLES OF STEEL.  DROVE TO KOBELCO AND DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND DISCOVERED 3 DRUMS HAD TURNED OVER, ONE HAD ROLLED ONTO THE STEEL AND WAS PUNCTURED.  CALLED FRONT LINE LEADER LARRY HALL,  WHO IN TURN CALLED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL, DEER PARK, TX TO PROPERLY CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF MATERIAL.  TRAILER WAS DECONED AS WELL.  DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELED CONCERNING THE IMPROPER LOADING.

AT ABOUT 3:00 AM ON MARCH 6, 2000 AN ASSOCIATED COURIERS INC DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE-VEHICLE ACCIDENT WHILE DELIVERING RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON I-64 AT MILE MARKER 33 ABOUT 28 MILES EAST OF DOWNTOWN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY.  A SEMI TRACTOR TRAILER DRIVER BEHIND OUR TRUCK REPORTED THE FOLLOWING EVENTS TO A STATE POLICE OFFICER.  OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING EAST WHEN HIS TRICK DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT (APPARENTLY STRIKING A GUARD RAIL). THE TRUCK THEN SWERVED LEFT INTO A ACROSS THE MEDIAN, ACROSS THE OTHER TRAFFIC LANES AND OFF THE OTHER SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THE TRUCK FLIPPED AND ROLLED THREE TIMES BEFORE COMING TO A STOP ON AN ENBANKMENT.  THE AIRBAG HAD DEPLOYED.  ALL PACKAGES CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WERE RETAINED INSIDE THE TRUCK.  NO RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WERE RELEASED FROM THE PRIMARY CONTAINERS ALTHOUGH SOME OF THE SECONDARY CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.  MOST OF THE EXTERIOR PACKAGING WAS BADLY DAMAGED.  ELEVEN [PACKAGES WERE FOR DELIVERY TO NUCLEAR PHARMACIES AND HOSPITALS.  THIRTEEN OTHER PACKAGES WERE BEING RETURNED TO THE SUPPLIERS ARE RECOVERABLE RESOURCES.  THESE ORIGINALLY CONTAINED RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS THAT HAD SINCE DECAYED AWAY.  THE STATE POLICE OFFICER NOTIFIED THE STATE RADIATION CONTROL DEPARTMENT, US (ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC) AND THE SUPPLIERS (DUPONT RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS AND MALLINCKRODT MEDICAL).  HE ALSO CALLED THE SYNCOR PHARMACY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY FOR ASSISTANCE AT THE SCENE. ACI NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  TWO RADIATION CONTROL MEMBERS AND THE SYNCOR MANAGER WHO RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT SURVEYED AND RELEASED THE TRUCK AND ALL PACKAGES.  ANOTHER SYNCOR INDIVIDUAL BROUGHT A TRUCK TO TRANSPORT THE PACKAGES TO SYNCOR FOR FINAL DISPOSITION.  OUR DRIVER SUSTAINED A HEAD INJURY AND A BROKEN RIB.  HE WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE UNIVERSITY OF LOUISVILLE HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. EMERGENCY SERVICES PERSONNEL CLEARED THE ACCIDENT SCENE BY 7:30 AM.

column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW ALERTED OF AN ODOR EMANATING FROM A TANK CAR IN THEIR TRAIN & TRAIN WAS STOPPED ON MAIN LINE.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) NOT APPLIED & BOTTON OUTLET VALVE (BOV) SLIGHTLY OPEN.  BOV CLOSED/BOC APPLIED.  ALSO, ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT & THE BOTTOM STEAM OUTLET PIPES UNPLUGGED.  BOLTS TOOL TIGHTENED & PLUGS APPLIED & TIGHTENED.  CAR/TRAIN RELEASED TO DESTINATION @ 0930 HRS CST. SPILLED PRODUCT ABSORBED BY PADS.
INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED CONTAINER VALVE BOX OPEN & MINOR VAPOR RELEASE FROM SAMPLE LINE VALVE.  BNSF RESPONDER TURNED SAMPLE LINE SCREW VALVE 1/4 TURN TO CLOSE & ELIMINATE VAPOR RELEASE.

INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED LOOSE OVERFLOW HOSE ON TANK CONTAINER WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO RELEASE ONTO CONTAINER & INTERMODAL FLATCAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS REATTACHED HOSE & CLEANED SPILLED PRODUCT.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: AT TIME OF ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL HOLE IN BOTTOM AT THE CHIME. THE DRUM WAS NOT LEAKING WHEN IT WAS AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY AND THERE WAS NOTHING IN THE FLOOR TO ACCOUNT FOR THE HOLE. CONSIGNEE PUT THE DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND ACCEPTED IT. THEY GAVE SOME OIL DRY TO ABSORB THE SPILLAGE.

AT TIME OF DELIVERY DRIVER SAW A SMALL SPOT OF LIQUID ON THE PALLET THAT THE DRUM WAS ON. HE AND THE CONSIGNEE OBSERVED THAT THE CLAMP RING OF THE DRUM WAS NOT TIGHT AND WAS COCKED, ALLOWING SPILLAGE TO OCCUR. CONSIGNEE RESEATED AND TIGHTENED THE RING BUT WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE DRUM. DRIVER TOOK IT TO CARRIERS NEAREST FACILITY. IT WAS INSPECTED THERE AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

ON ARRIVAL THE CARRIER'S LOCAL FACILITY , THE PICK UP DRIVER OBSERVED SOME SPILLAGE OF MATERIAL. THE DRIVER CHECKED AND FOUND THAT THE CLAMP RING BOLT WAS BENT AND COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED SUFFICIENTLY TO PROPERLY SECURE THE RING. THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR A REPLACEMENT. NO  CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.

PAIL WAS ON THE BOTTOM OF A PALLET WITH ANOTHER TIER OF THE SAME PRODUCT ABOVE IT. A PALLET OF SOME OTHER MATERIAL WAS STACKED ON TOP OF THAT PALLET. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS CRACKED ON ITS BOTTOM AND HAD LOST ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS. CONSIGNEE NOTED THAT DAMAGE, ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR AND KEPT THE EMPTY PAIL FOR DISPOSAL.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: MATERIAL HAD BEEN OFFERED FOR DELIVERY EARLIER. IT HAD BEEN REFUSED BECAUSE THE SHIPPER PALLET HAD PROTRUDING NAILS IN THEM. THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE CARRIERS FACILITY AND REPALLETIZED. WHEN LOADING FOR DELIVERY CARRIERS DOCK PERSON DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM A SMALL HOLE IN ONE PAIL. PAIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET SECURED AND HELD OFF TO AWAIT SHIPPERS INSTRUCTIONS.

WHEN UNLOADING A CARTON WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE FALLEN DURING TRANSIT. THE CARTON WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING A BAG WAS DISCOVERED WITH A HOLE RUBBED IN THE SIDE CAUSED BY A RIVET IN THE TRAILER SIDE. THE BAG WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING A PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WITH A PIN HOLE IN THE BOTTOM HEAD OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT SALVAGE APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE CAP. THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE PAIL. THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: ON 032500 AT APPROXIMATELY 430 P.M. MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION. GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER REPORTING THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN AN OUTBOUND TRACK AT ENGLEWOOD YARD IN HOUSTON,  TEXAS.  THE LEAK WAS REPORTED AS 3-4 DROPS PER MINUTE, COMING FROM THE TOP.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER OBSERVED THE LIQUID COMING FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE STANDARD CAR SEAL ON THE HOUSING WAS ALREADY BROKEN.  THE SEAL NUMBER IS ROHM & HASS TX 130398.  REEDER OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND SAW LIQUID SEEPING FROM UNDER THE LIQUID VALVE WHERE IT WAS THREADED ONTO THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  REEDER REMOVED THE PLUG FROM THE AIR VALVE, OPENED IT TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE AND STOP THE LEAK.  ONCE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, REEDER REVOVED THE LIQUID VALVE, CLEANED THE THREADS, APPLIED NEW TEFLON TAPE, AND REPLACED THE VALVE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR NORMAL TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

UPRR PERSONNEL AT FREEPORT CONTACTED CONSIGNEE DOW CHEMICAL, TO RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF SHIPPER.  DOW RESPONSE TEAM DISCOVERED A BROKEN PIPE NIPPLE AT THE AIR VALVE ON TOP OF TANK CAR.  CORRECTIVE ACTION ENTAILED REMOVING PART OF PIPE NIPPLE THREADED INTO BASE AND INSTALLING A PLUG.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED AT 15:30 3/24/00 AND SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY INTO DOW CHEMICAL PLANT AT FREEPORT, TX.

column168: A TRACTOR WAS PULLED OVER ALONG INTERSTATE 95 IN HARFORD COUNTY, MARYLAND BY THE HIGHWAY PATROL BECAUSE A LIQUID WAS COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE VAN. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE CALLED IN AND NORTHBOUND. INTERSTATE 95 WAS CLOSED DOWN FOR TWO HOURS. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE TRAILER, BUT THE LEAKING DRUM COULD NOT BE FOUND. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE SOUTHBOUND PERRYVILLE TRUCK SCALE AND HELD IN THE SPILL CONTAINMENT AREA. THE DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO A DIFFERENT TRAILER AND THE LEAKING DRUM OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. 20 GALLONS OF THE PAINT WASTE WAS SPILLED FROM THE DRUM. THIS WAS DUE TO A PINHOLE LEAK CAUSED BY CORROSION ON THE BOTTOM SEAM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 250 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET, IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT/ DISPOSAL. column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO A 20,000 GALLON TANK WITH TWO DUAL POINT DROPS.  THE TRUCK EMPTIED AND HE UNHOOKED THE HOSES.  THE TRAILER WAS STILL UNLOADING AND WHEN HE TURNED AROUND HE HEARD THE TANK GURGLE AND PRODUCT STARTED COMING OUT OF THE FILL PIPE.  DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE BUT THE CONTAINMENT BOX OVERFLOWED AND APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS SPILLED.  THE DRIVER USED KITTY LITER TO CONTAIN AND MOP UP THE SPILL.  ABOUT A QUART OF PRODUCT DID GO INTO A STATION DRAIN AND WAS CLEANED WITH SPILL PADS.  STATION MANAGER CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CLEARED THE LOT OF CUSTOMERS.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OPENED THE STATION BACK UP IN ABOUT 20 MINUTES. FIRE DEPARTMENT TOLD THE DRIVER THAT HE DID A GOOD JOB OF CONTROLLING AND CLEANING UP THE SPILL.  THE STATION HAS 2 DRAIN SYSTEMS.  THE INNER SYSTEM, WHICH IS THE DRAIN THAT DID GET ABOUT A QUART OF PRODUCT, IS SELF CONTAINED AND FLOWS TO A 8,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND TANK.  EH&S COORDINATOR WAS CONTACTED AND WILL HAVE THE SYSTEM CHECKED.  ALL SPILL MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: ON MARCH 16,2000 OUR DRIVER PICKED UP LAMPS AND MERCURY CONTAINING DEVICES AND BOTTLES OF ELEMENTAL MERCURY AT BON SECOR HOSPITAL IN VENICE, FL. THE TRUCK WAS OFF LOADED ON THE 17TH AT SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES, INC. FACILITY IN PLANT CITY, FL AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM. AFTER UNLOADING THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY WITH THIS TRUCK TO BEGIN HIS NEXT SCHEDULED ROUTE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 12:15 P.M., A FACILITY TECHNICIAN WAS PREPARING TO TRANSFER THE PACKAGE CONTAINING THE BOTTLES OF ELEMENTAL MECURY TO THE MECURY DEVICE STORAGE ROOM. IN THE PROCESS OF MOVING THE PACKAGE, HE NOTICED A BEAD OF ELEMENTAL MERCURY ON THE WOODEN PALLET CARRYING THE PACKAGE.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED RALPH MANN, OPERATIONS MANAGER.  THE MERCURY WAS THEN CLEANED OF THE PALLET USING A MERCURY VACUUM.  THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE WERE INSPECTED TO ASCERTAIN THE SOURCE OF THE SPILLED MERCURY.  A 4 OZ. PLASTIC BOTTLE CONTAINED IN THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE EMPTY.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THIS CONTAINER REVEALED A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BOTTLE.  ALL OTHER CONTAINERS APPEARED TO BE INTACT AN DNON-LEAKING.  THE IMMEDIATE AEA OF THE PLANT WAS ALSO CLEANED WITH THE VACUUM.  AN INSPECTION OF HTE FACILITY REVEALED THAT SEVERAL BEADS OF MERCURY WERE PRESENT AT THE BASE OF THE RAMP IN THE LOADING DOCK AREA.  THIS AREAWAS ALSO CLEANED FOLLOWING THE SAME PROCEDURES AS WERE USED IN CLEANING THE PLANT.  AIRMONITORING WAS PERFORMED WITH THE JEROME MERCURY VAPOR ANALYZER.  RESULTS OF THE AIR MONITORING ARE ATTACHED.  SINCE THE EXACT TIME OF THE PACKAGE FAILURE WAS NOT KNOWN, THE DRIVER WAS CONTACTED AND INSTRUCTED TO IMMEDIATELY RETURN TO THE PLANT.  UPON ARRIVAL THE TRUCK WAS INSPECTED FOR THE PRESENCE ON MERCURY.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE PACKAGE FAILURE OCCURED EITHER IN THE TRUCK OR PRIOR TO LOADING.  BON SECOR HOSPITAL WAS NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED TO INSPEC THEIR STORAGE AREA FOR SIGNS OF SPILLAGE.  THEY REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE IN THEIR STORAGE AREA.  MEANWHILE, FACILITY PERSONNEL UNLOADED AND CLEANED THE TRUCK.  AIR MONITORING WAS PERFORMED IN THE TRUCK TO VERIFY THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE CLEANING.  LATER THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED AGAIN USING A MERCURY SPILL CLEAN UP PRODUCT CALLED "HGX".  BASED ON THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RECOVERED FROM THE PALLET AND PLANT AREA, THE LOADING DOCK, AND INSIDE THE TRUCK, IT APPEARED THAT LESS THAN ONE POUND OF MERCURY WAS RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGE.  ON MARCH 21, 2000 THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED BY MIKE FLYNN, GENERAL MANAGER - FLORIDA OPERATIONS, AND PHILLIP DITTER, APPROVALS MANAGER.  BASED ON THE RESULTS OF THIS REVIEW THE FOLLOWING CONCLUSIONS WERE REACHED.

A FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A TRUCK AND UNKNOWING PUNCTURED THE DRUM WHEN HE PICKED UP A PIECE OF FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THE DRUM. A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED AND THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED. THE STEEL DRUM WAS INSERTED INTO THE DANGEROUS GOODS BARREL ALONG WITH SPILLED DEBRIS. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS :DRUMS WILL BE LOADED TO REAR OF TRUCKS.

WHILE UNLOADING , ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING 4, 1- GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO OF THE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED AND TWO WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO TOP HEAVY FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARTON. THE TWO DAMAGED CONTAINERS, DUNNAGE,  AND THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED BOXES, EACH CONTAINING FIFTEEN, ONE QUART GLASS CONTAINERS, WERE DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS WAS DUE TO BEING PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND SPILL X.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AND DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO TWO FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS.  THE PAILS WERE THEN PLACED INTO A FIFTY FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM.  THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWENTY FIVE UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE REPACKAGED AND WERE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

FOUR SEASONS COMPLETED THE CLEANUP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE ABSORBENT WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL FACILITY IN CHARLOTTE, NORTH CAROLINA FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: HERCULES DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF NATURAL GASOLINE ON I-45 IN HOUSTON TEXAS WHEN HE OBSERVED A PASSING MOTORIST FLAGGING HIM TO A PROBLEM ON HIS TRAILER. UPON STOPPING AND INVESTIGATING, THE DRIVER OBSERVED FLUID SPURTING FROM A BONNET VALVE ON THE TRAILER BELLY PIPING. THE DRIVE TIGHTENED THE BONNET CAUSING THE LEAK TO DIMINISH, BUT WAS INSTRUCTED BY TX-DPS TO PULL TO THE NEXT INTERSECTION FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION AND EVALUATION. UPON, PULLING INTO AN ABANDONED PARKING LOT AT THE INTERSECTION OF RAFORD AND SAWDUST, FLUID WAS THEN OBSERVED COMING FROM A FLANGE AREA OF THE BELLY PIPING. TX-DPS THEN ORDERED THE VEHICLE TO BE OFF-LOADED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IN CONJUNCTION WITH CITY MAINTENANCE CREWS CONTAINED AND CONTROLLED THE SPILL WITH A SAND AND EARTHEN DAM ON THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT AND THE EDGE OF THE GROUND SURFACE. THE DAMAGED CARGO TANKER WAS OFF-LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TANKER WITHIN 3 HOURS OF THE INCIDENT. A PROFESSIONAL SPILL CLEAN-UP CREW, BOOTS AND COOTS, REMOVED THE RESIDUE AND CONTAMINATED SOILS. ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE DEPOSITED IN A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER: PRESENTLY, STORED AT THE LAPORTE TERMINAL AND BEING PROCESSED FOR A PROPER DISPOSAL. NO FURTHER CLEAN-UP IS REQUIRED AT THIS TIME. THE DAMAGE CONTAINER WAS SENT TO INTANK TANK, INC. FOR REPAIRS.

UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR TO INSPECT THE LOAD. DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID ON TRAILER FLOOR AND A SMALL AMOUNT ESCAPED THE TRAILER.   AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED. THEY RESPONDED, CLEANED SPILL OVERPACKED LEAKING DRUM, TRANSLOADED TO A TRAILER WITH SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. PUT EQUIPMENT BACK INTO SERVICE. SITUATION:   PETRON WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO A TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT TRUCK WHICH HAD A LEAKING DRUM OF ACETONE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE STATE POLICE CLOSED DOWN HWY 80 AND FIVE BUSINESSES NEAR THE INCIDENT. ONE PERSON WAS EVACUATED FROM A RESIDENCE ACROSS THE STREET FROM THE INCIDENT AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. ONCE THE SITE WAS SECURED, PETRON PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER TO TRY AND DETERMINE WHICH DRUM OR DRUMS WERE LEAKING. THIS COULD NOT BE ACCOMPLISHED BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS FILLED TO CAPACITY SO THE DECISION WAS MADE TO REMOVE THE DRUMS FROM THE TRAILER. MIDWAY THROUGH THIS PROCESS, THE LEAKING DRUM WAS FOUND AND OVERPACKED. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER TO MAKE SURE THERE WAS NOT ANOTHER LEAK AND TO FACILITATE CLEANING THE FLOOR. THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN THE FLOOR WERE PLACED INTO THE OVERPACKED DRUM WITH THE LEAKING CONTAINER.   (EIGHT OTHER DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AT THE DIRECTION OF THE STATE POLICE DUE TO THE CONDITION OF THE DRUMS) ONCE ALL THE DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE, THEY WERE LOADED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER AND SENT ON TO THE LANDFILL. THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES TO PERSONNEL AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. HWY 80 WAS CLOSED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME WHILE THE CLEAN-UP WAS IN PROGRESS.

THE PALLET OF BATTERIES WERE BEING STAGED TO BE LOADED ABOARD A FEDEX AIRCRAFT. THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED.  BAKING SODA WAS APPLIED TO THE UNKNOWN SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL BUBBLED UP JUST LIKE BATTERY ACID DOES. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AS THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. I SPOKE TO LAURA RENNER WITH THE FAA.
THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE FEDEX STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD PENDING DISPOSITION INFORMATION FROM THE SHIPPER.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING BOTH INNER AND OUTER UNITS TO RUPTURE ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER.RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

SINCE THIS WAS A MIXTURE OF GAS AND EXTINGUISHING POWDER, THE AMOUNT SPILLED COULD NOT BE DETERMINED BY THE SPILL SPECIALIST WHO CLEANED UP THIS SPILL. THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY. UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION COMES IN FROM THE SHIPPER THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD IN A SECURE AREA.

THE DRIVER INSPECTED HIS EQUIPMENT WHILE STOPPED IN A REST AREA ON ROUTE 71 IN JEFFERSON OHIO AND OBSERVED A WET SPOT ON HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER PLACED PLASTIC SHEETING AND FLOOR DRY UNDER HIS UNIT. THE DRIVER PHONED HIS SAFETY DEPARTMENT WHO IN TURN CONTACTED CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE REST AREA OVER-PACKED THE DRUM AND REMOVED THE PLASTIC AND FLOOR DRY. THE DRIVER DELIVERED THE COMPLETE LOAD INCLUDING THE MATERIALS USED BY THE CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF CINCINNATI, OH WHICH WAS THE FINAL DESTINATION FOR THE LOAD.
DRIVER DID NOT HEAR THE VENT ALARM CUT OFF.

column168: A DRIVER CAME TO ME TO TELL ME THERE WAS A SPILL ON THE TRAILER HE WAS STRIPPING.  HE HAD TAKEN A TALL SKID OUT W/HIS FORKLIFT, AND WHEN HE WENT BACK IN THE TRAILER, HE SAW A SMALL BOX TURNED OVER ON IT'S SIDE WITH A DUNNAGE SKID LAYING ON TOP OF IT.  I PLACED 'SPEEDY-DRY' ON THE SPILL TO CONTAIN IT UNTIL THE FIRE DEPT. CAME. THE F.D. ARRIVED AND THEN WE CALLED 'D-TOX', OUR CONTRACT CLEANER FOR HAZ-MAT.  THEY THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE.  THERE WAS ONE BUNDLE OF BUTCHER BLOCK NATIVE WOOD UNDERNEATH THE CORROSIVE BOXES THAT WAS STAINED FROM THE SPILL.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED IN HARRISBURG PA ON TRAILER 285940 AND DURING UNLOADING DOCKWORKER FOUND THAT 1 CTNS HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND ADHESIVE WAS LEAKING OUT OF CTNS.  CTN WAS OVERPACKED IN DRUM AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS

UPON ARRIVAL AT SEPARATE DELIVERY LOCATION, DRIVER FOUND OBSERVED LEAKAGE FROM SUBJECT DRUM INSIDE TRAILER AND ON GROUND SURFACE. COMPANY SAFETY PERSONNEL AND CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR (FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL) WERE DISPATCHED TO SCENE TO OVERPACK LEAKING DRUM AND PERFORM NECESSARY CLEAN-UP/DECONTAMINATION OF TRAILER FLOOR AND SOILS/GROUND SURFACES AFFECTED BY THE SPILLAGE.  NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED AND MITIGATION ACTIVITIES WERE PERFORMED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON, CONTAINING SIX, ONE GALLON CANS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE, ONE GALLON CAN WAS DAMAGED.  THE OTHER FIVE CANS WERE UNAFFECTED.   APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP.  THE DAMAGED CAN AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: THIS CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING WHILE IN TRAIN MOVEMENT AT OUR YARD I NEW ORLEANS, LA.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS FOUND LOOSE, AND NO MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS FOUND UNDER THE COVER.  A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTIONS FOUND TO CAR. column168: ON 3/39/00, THE TRAINMASTER I NASHVILLE, TN A CALL FROM A LOCAL BUSINESS REPORTING AN ODOR COMING FROM THE AREA NEAR CST TRANSFLO FACILITY IN NASHVILLE.  INVESTIGATION BY THE TRANSFLO MANAGER REVEALED THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM GATX 87205 ON THE CSXT MAIN LINE. A CSXT HAZMAT CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND SEVERAL MANWAY BOLTS ON THE CAR.  NO LIQUID SPILL WAS EVIDENT.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

GATX 6892, LD SULFURIC ACID, REPORTED BY CREW TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CXST'S RAIL YARD IN DAYTON, OH.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1030 HOURS.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED PEOPLE FROM THEIR LIMA, OH FACILITY.  THE SHIPPER FOUND THE CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE SHIPPER DID NOT HAVE A PROPER REPLACEMENT DISK.  A SOLID STEEL DISK WAS INSTALLED SO THE CAR COULD BE MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING.  THE SHIPPER WILL SEND THE PROPER RUPTURE DISK TO THE CONSIGNEE TO INSTALL BEFORE THE RESIDUE IS RELEASED.

GATX 723610 WAS OBSERVED WITH A SLOSH LEAK IN TRACK B19 AT THE CSXT YARD IN LOUISVILLE, KY.  THE CONDUCTOR WORKING THE TRIM JOB WAS SPLASHED ON THE ARM WITH THE PRODUCT, THE CONDUCTOR WAS NOT INJURED. CSXT HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS NOT IN THE PROPER POSITION, IT WAS ASKEW AND WAS NOT PROVIDING A COMPLETE SEAL.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE ALL TOOL TIGHT.  THE CSXT HAZMAT DEPARTMENT ADJUSTED THE MANWAY GASKET TO PROVIDE FOR A COMPLETE SEAL OF THE MANWAY CLOSURE.

UTLX 80004 WAS INVOLVED IN A SLOW SPEED DERAILMENT THAT DAMAGED THE HAND BRAKE AND CROSSOVER PLATFORM ON THE B-END AND CREASED THE JACKET ON THE BL CORNER.  THE JACKET WAS NOT PENETRATED.  THE CAR BEGAN TO VENT THE FOLLOWING DAY WHILE IN THE CAR SHOP FOR REPAIRS. THE PRESSURE WHEN CHECKED BY CSXT HAZMAT WAS 45lbs.  THE CAR WAS PULLED FROM THE SHOP AND THE SLOSHING MOVEMENT OF THE PRODUCT HELPED TO DROP THE VAPOR PRESSURE TO 38 lbs.  THE CAR WAS MONITORED FOR 2 HOURS WITH NO RISE IN PRESSURE.  THE CAR WAS PLACED IN THE OUTBOUND TRAIN FOR DELIVERY THAT EVENING TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE PRESSURE WHEN RECEIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE WAS 38lbs.
ONE CYLINDER WAS DAMAGED AT THE VALVE.  THE CYLINDER WAS ALLOWED TO VENT AND THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. MATERIAL HANDLER WAS UNLOADING 6500 GALLONS OF D-LIMONENE FROM A LIQUID TRANSPORT TRAILER ONTO AN ASHLAND 5-HOLE COMPARTMENTED TRAILER.  THE TRAILER HAD A CAPACITY OF 8500 GALLONS AND THERE WAS ALREADY 1100 GALLONS IN COMPARTMENT #5 OF THE TRAILER.  THE MATERIAL HANDLER FILLED COMPARTMENT #1 AND #2, WHICH HAD CAPACITIES OF 2500 AND 1000 GALLONS, RESPECTIVELY.  HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF SHUTTING A VALVE AFTER FILLING COMPARTMENT #3 WHEN PRODUCT OVERFLOWED FROM TOP OF TRAILER SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO SCALE. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND ASHLAND'S EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS CALLED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT MATERIAL HANDLER HAD CALCULATED HIS ENDING WEIGHT FOR FILLING COMPARTMENT #3 WRONG AND AS A RESULT PUT TOO MUCH PRODUCT IN TRAILER AND ALSO THE OUT-A-ALARM DEVICE ON TRAILER DID NOT SOUND OFF.  IN THE FUTURE WE WILL GET WEIGHT TICKETS FOR EACH COMPARTMENT FILLED INSTEAD OF FOR THE WHOLE TRUCK.  THE MATERIAL HANDLE WILL BE RETRAINED ON BEST LOADING PROCEDURES AS COMPARTMENT #5 COULD HAVE BEEN FILLED FIRST TO PREVENT HAVING TO FILL TO CAPACITY ON OTHER 4 COMPARTMENTS.

WHILE STILL AT HIS ORIGINAL LOCATION, THE DRIVER FOUND BLACK PAINT LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OF TWO DRUMS. CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER PLACE ABSORBENT PADS AROUND THE DRUMS AND CONTINUE TO THE CORRECT CONSIGNEE WHICH WS NEARBY. column168: CAR CAME ONTO HIGHWAY FROM ON RAMP. TRUCK IN FRONT APPLIED BRAKES. USF HOLLAND DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES. FELT FREIGHT SLIDE. WENT ON DOWN HIGHWAY UNTIL HE COULD SAFELY PULL OVER AND CHECK FREIGHT. SAW THAT THERE WAS A LEAK. RETURNED TO FORT WAYNE TERMINAL. LEAKING DRUMS WERE PULLED OFF TRAILER AND PUT IN TERMINAL YARD ON THEIR SIDES ON A SKID. PIG PUTTY WAS MIXED AND APPLIED TO HOLE IN SIDE OF EACH DRUM (OTHER FREIGHT HAD SLID INTO THE DRUMS CAUSING THEM TO BEND & SMALL HOLE MADE IN EACH BEND). DRUMS WERE THEN PUT IN RECOVERY DRUMS. SAND WAS APPLIED TO SPILLS ON TRAILER AS PER LABELS ON DRUMS. SAND PUT INTO RECOVERY DRUM. THE REST OF THE FREIGHT WAS PUT ON ANOTHER TRAILER & TAKEN TO GLOBE VALVE & LEFT FOR LOADING THE NEXT DAY. ON 3/7 REC'D CALL FROM JEFF OF GLOBE VALVE THAT SECRETARY HAD GONE ON THAT SECOND TRAILER TO TAG FREIGHT AND BECAME ILL. WAS TAKEN TO COMPANY NURSE WHERE SHE APPEARED TO BE FINE AFTER 1 1/2 HOURS. GLOBE CALLED CHEMTREC & ASHLAND CHEMICAL. USF HOLLAND NOTIFIED ASHLAND CHEMICAL FOR DISPOSITION ON DRUMS.

PART TIME HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIANS MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND MICHAEL COOK DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX PROPERLY MARKED,  LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS:  PAINT, CLASS 3, UN1283, PGIII.  THE BOX WAS LABELED WITH THE CLASS 3 LABEL, CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY LABEL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND BLUE PAINT LEAKING INSIDE THE BOX AND FOUND BLUE PAINT LEAKING INSIDE THE BOX.  THEY INSPECTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE BOX AND FOUND, 8 X 1 PINT METAL CANS EACH WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES WITH POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  ONE OF THE METAL PINT CANS HAD AN UNSECURE CLOSURE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 3 OUNCES OF THE BLUE PAINT.  ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE 3 X 1 QUART METAL CANS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES WITH POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  NONE OF THE METAL QUART CANS LEAKED.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL INSIDE THE BOX.  THEY REPLACED THE METAL CANS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT ON TO DESTINATION.  ALL MARKINGS, LABELS AND CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WERE DUPLICATED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE RECOVERY DRUM BEFORE DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THE EMPLOYEE WHO REPORTED THE ODOR WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO FOLLOW UP MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:20   A COPY OF THE CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

column168: A CALL CAME IN TO OUR DISPATCH THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AND AMMITING AN ODOR OF POSSIBLY GASOLINE AT OUR SORT FACILITY IN SECONDARY 7, BUILDING LOCATED AT ABX AIR Inc. AS THE SPILL TECHNICIANS APPROACHED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION THEY NOTICED THAT THE ADVERTISEMENT ON THE LARGE BOX STATED THAT IT WAS A CHORE MASTER PRESSURE WASHER WITH A COLORED PICTORIAL OF THE PRESSURE WASHER, WHICH ALSO SHOWED THAT THE THERE MAY POSSIBLY BE A GAS TANK INVOLVED.  THEY ALSO NOTED THAT THERE WERE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTERMOST PACKAGING.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION THEY DID IN FACT DISCOVER A BRIGGS & STRATTON PIECE OF EQUIPMENT AND THERE WAS IN FACT A GASOLINE TANK AND THAT IT HAD BEEN LEAKING.  THE LEAK WAS DUE TO THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION MOVING THROUGH THE SORT FACILITY BUILDINGS VIA SEVERAL CONVEYOR BELTS AND ORIENTATION OF THE SHIPMENT WOULD HAVE BEEN IMPOSSIBLE, THEREFORE AS THE SHIPMENT TRAVELED AND POSSIBLY TURNING ON ITS SIDE OR UPSIDE DOWN THE TANK SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BAGGED IN 3 HEAVY LARGE WHITE AIRBORNE EXPRESS BAGS AND REMOVED FROM SECONDARY 7 OF BUILDING AND TAKEN TO THE HAZMAT SORT SECURITY CAGE AND PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.
DURING INSPECTION,LEAKAGE NOTED AT HANDLE ATTACHMENTS TO DRUM. PACKAGE IN STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

AN ODOR WAS COMING FROM THIS FEDEX PAK WHICH WAS SET ASIDE FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  WHEN THIS PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND INSPECTED, 2 BOTTLES OF FINGERNAIL POLISH WERE FOUND(ALONG WITH SHAMPOO).  ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN.  THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS WERE FOUND ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  AFTER THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY BY THE LOCAL SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNTIL THE FAA ALLOWS FEDEX TO RELEASE THIS SHIPMENT.

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK ON MAR 8, 2000 APR 14:35P.M.BY BILL PERATT IN OUR MARINE DEPARTMENT.  WE WERE STEVEDORING TANK TPTU840006-9 IN BERTH 6 FROM THE PORT OF HOUSTON FOR THIRD PARTY STEAMSHIP COMPANY,  OOCL(ORIENT OVERSEAS CONTAINER LINES).  THE TANK WAS TO SAIL ON OUR VESSEL THE NEWARK BAY 646E.  THE CAPTAIN OF THE VESSEL NOTIFIED MARINE HE SMELLED AN ODOR AND APPEARED PRODUCT MAYBE LEAKING.  THE TANK WAS LIFTED OFF THE VESSEL AND ISOLATED IN BERTH 3, ROW 113.  THERE WERE NO PERSONNEL OR ACTIVITIES OCCURRING IN THIS ROW.  I CONTACTED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE VENDOR BOOTS AND COOTS TO COME TO OUR FACILITY TO ASSIST.  ALSO CONTACTED HARVEY MILLER WITH OOCL TO ADVISE NAME OF SHIPPER AND CONTACTS.  I WAS TOLD THE SHIPPER WAS HOYER.  I WAS GIVEN A CONTACT OF BRENDA JANSEN AT 713-740-7400 TO CONTACT.  SHE ADVISED THEY WOULD SEND THEIR TANK SPECIALIST.  OUR MARINE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT BEFORE THE TANK WAS MOVED TO 113.  THE PORT PUT A POP-UP POOL UNDERNEATH THE TANK TO KEEP ANY PRODUCT FROM LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND.  THE POH FIRE DEPARTMENT TIGHTENED LOOSE NUTS AND BOLTS AROUND THE FLANGE/VALVE.  THIS APPEARED TO STOP THE LEAK.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE SCENE THE TANK APPEARED TO STOP LEAKING.  THE PORT OF HOUSTON SECURITY WAS ALSO ON SCENE.  I CALLED NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 3:40P.M.  OFFICER GARNEAU ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER 522342. ALSO NOTIFIED TNRCC BY PHONE AND ADVISED I WOULD SEND A FOLLOW REPORT.  BOB CERON OF BAKER PETROLITE CONTACTED ME TO ADVISE THEY WERE OWNERS OF THE PRODUCT.  SHIPPER OF PRODUCT SHOWED HOYER ODFJELL INC.  ON THE PAPERWORK.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAP AND PART OF THE CONNECTING VALVE HAD BEEN SEVERED OFF THE TANK AND THE VALVE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN JAMMED.  THE VALVE WAS SITTING DOWN ON THE FRAME OF THE TANK. ALSO APPEARED TO HAVE A FINE HAIRLINE WELD CRACK BY THE VALVE WHERE THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED.  CMS INTERMODAL TEAM BROUGHT IN A NEW VALVE/CAP, GASKET AND REPLACED WITHOUT ANY LEAKS. THE TANK WAS LIFTED OFF THE STEVEDORING CHASSIS AND PLACED ONTO CMS INTERMODAL DROP DECK FRAME.  THE TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE TERMINAL AT 7:45 P.M.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE TANK. ABSORBENT HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE GROUND UNDER THE POP-UP POOL. BOOTS AND COOTS CLEANED UP THE SPILL, PLACED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS INTO A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM, LABELED OUTSIDE OF DRUM. BOOTS AND COOTS DECONNED CHASSIS MAEC741948 BEFORE IT WAS RELEASED FOR SERVICE.  CLEAN UP ENDED AT 1900.  BAKER PETROLITE PICKED UP THE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL ON MARCH 14 TO HANDLE PROPER DISPOSAL OF MATERIALS.  THE TANK WAS NOT LEAKING WHEN WE PICKED IT UP FROM THE PORT OF HOUSTON TO STEVEDORE TO THE VESSEL.  I WAS ADVISED THE TANK HAD MOVED BY RAIL TO HOUSTON THEN DRAYED TO PORT OF HOUSTON TERMINAL.  IT IS SPECULATED THAT THE TANK WAS DAMAGED WHILE IN POSSESSION OF THE RAILROAD.  THE TANK WAS NOT OBSERVED LEAKING AT TIME OF ARRIVAL IN PORT GATE OR WHEN STEVEDORED TO VESSEL, IT WAS VERY EASY TO OVERLOOK A CAP WAS MISSING.

column168: CAR ARRIVED IN POCATELLO ON TRAIN QNPHKB 02.  ED BANKS, ENIVORNMENT ENIGEER, NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. VALVE HANDLE WAS ABOUT ONE-THIRD OPEN AND LOCKING PIN WAS HANGING FREE.  VALVE CAP WAS IN PLACE AND TIGHT BUT PRODUCT CONTINUED TO SEEP OUT INDICATING A DEFECTIVE GASKET.  THE LOCKING PIN ITSELF IS DEFECTIVE IN THAT ITS HEAD IS MISSING.  MR. BANKS CLOSED THE VALVE, INSERTED THE LOCKING PIN AND WIRED IT INTO PLACE.  THE LEAK RATE HAD BEEN SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE AND ABOUT HALF A CUP OF PRODUCT ACTUALLY LEAKED ONTO THE BALLAST AND QUICKLY EVAPORATED.  APPLIED EMG SEAL #008902.  MR. BANKS THEN CONTACTED METHANEX, ADVISING THEM TO REPLACE THE LOCKING PIN AND CHECK THE GASKET BEFORE LOADING THE CAR AGAIN.

column168: MGR. RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM ROSS CAR FORMAN AT ROPER YARD.  HE STATED THAT HE HAD A CAR IN THE YARD TRACK 15.  MGR. RODABOUGH CONDUCTED INSPECTION OF SAID CAR AND FOUND, A BROKEN FRANGIBLE DISC, ALSO NOTED THAT THE FOUR SWING BOLTS HOLDING THE MANWAY IN PLACE WERE IN BAD ORDER, ONE WAS COMPLETELY MISSING, ONE WAS BROKEN AND STILL ON THE CAR, ONE WAS BENT STILL IN PLACE THE OTHER WAS IN PLACE BUT LOOSE.  MGR. RODABOUGH MADE CONTACT WITH MR. DALE VINCENT OF THE THATCHER CHEMICAL AND ARRANGED FOR A JOINT INSPECTION OF THE CAR WITH MR. STACY JACOBS, ALSO OF THATCHER CHEMICAL.  AFTER THE JOINT INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR COULD NOT BE REPAIRED.  ON 03/15/2000 MGR. RODABOUGH AND TWO LABORERS FROM PACIFIC WEST PERFORMED A TRANSLOAD OPERATION MOVING THE PRODUCT FROM TANKCAR GATX 41093 TO TANKCAR RTMX 13589. TRANSLOAD OPERATION COMMENCED AT 0930 AND WAS COMPLETE AT 1140 SAME DATE.

column168: W. M. SEABAUGH, MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ADVISED BY RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER THAT TANK CAR GATX 10399 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT UPRR VOLASCO YARD.  MGR. ENVIRONMENT REMEDIATION, GEOFF REEDER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA A VOICE MAIL MESSAGE FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, JAY EVERETT.  A CARMAN MAKING AN INSPECTION OF THE TRAIN DISCOVERED THE RELEASE. EVERETT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, BASF, WHO SENT A LOCAL RESPONSE TEAM. THE SHIPPER REPAIRED THE MANWAY GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLTS.  THE TRAIN WAS DELAYED FOR ABOUT 2 HOURS WHILE REPAIRS WERE MADE.  CHEMTREC, MARK PETERSON, WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 03102000-008

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 03/22/2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 HRS.  MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  JOHN REYNA, CAR FOREMAN, ADVISED THE LEAK WAS A STEADY DRIP AND WAS FORMING A POOL ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THEIR WORK AREA.  REYNA WAS DIRECTED TO PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS TO CATCH THE DRIP.  UPON ARRIVAL REEDER DISCOVERED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE SEAL BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE TANK.  REEDER ATTEMPTED TO LIGHTEN THE BOLTS BUT, WAS UNSUCCESSFUL DUE TO INSUFFICIENT CLEARANCE FOR THE WRENCH TO TURN. SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WITH A VARIETY OF DIFFERENT STYLE WRENCHES WAS TRIED, THOUGH ALL WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  RECAR ARRIVED AND ALSO ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTENED THE NUTS.  THEIR TOOLS ALSO WOULD NOT WORK. A WRENCH WAS THEN HEATED WITH A TORCH AND BENT TO AN ANGEL THAT WOULD ALLOW IT TO FIT INSIDE THE SKID PROTECTION AREA.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED AT 1130 HRS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  ALL CONTRACTORS WERE HIRED BY THE SHIPPER.  THERE ARE NO CHARGES TO UPRR.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE BAGGED AND DISPOSED OF IN THE DUMPSTER.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE TRAIN 263-08 WAS RECEIVING PULL BY INSPECTION FROM CAR INSPECTORS AT SARATOGA STATION, THEY NOTICED WETNESS ON TANK CAR, THEY IMMEDIATELY STOPPED MOVEMENT AND REPORTED THE SITUATION TO THE NETWORK MANAGEMENT CENTER.  CARS WERE ISOLATED AWAY FROM STATION. FIELD MANAGER, TOM WILSON WAS DISPATCHED OUT OF SARATOGA TO ASSESS SITUATION.  HE ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 19:10  AND EXAMINATION OF CARS REVEALED THE FOLLOWING DEFECTS.  GATX 44600 LEAKING AT THE BREATHER VENT VALVE, GATX 44594 LEAKING AT THE PSI SAFETY VALVE, AND GATX 44598 LEAKING AT THE 6" VALVE ON TOP OF CAR AT "B" END.  WETNESS WAS RESTRICTED TO  THE ABOVE AREAS AND PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATING DUE TO AMBIENT TEMPERATURE AND THEREFORE PRODUCT LOSS CEASED AS AMBIENT TEMPERATURE DECREASED.  MR. WILSON CONTACTED CHEMTREC (US) 1-800-424-9300 19:45, (TRACY) AND REQUESTED SHIPPER BE ADVISED TO CALL HIM.  MR. E LEDOVE, EXXON MOBIL CALLED AT 20:27.  AFTER LEARNING THE PROBLEM SAID HE WOULD HAVE HIS PRODUCT MANAGER, RAIL CALL HIM.  MR. KRATZBERG, PRODUCT MANAGER.  MR. KRATZBERG SAID HE HAD CONTACTED HIS LOCAL MANAGER WHO WOULD BE CALLING ME.  MR. TOM JAMISON, MANAGER, EXXON MOBIL, ALBANY, 518-365-6560 CALLED AT 21:05. MR. JAMISON SAID HE WAS EN ROUTE WITH HIS FOREMAN, MR. S. ANDRETTI, ANT THAT HE HAD ALSO CONTACTED GATX WHO WERE ALSO EN ROUTE, MR. JAMISON AND MR. ANDRETTI ARRIVED AT 21:30.  MR.KEN KOLIADA AND MR. RANDY GREENE, GATX ARRIVED AT 21:50.  AFTER EXAMINATION OF THE 3 CARS, IT WAS DECIDED TO WAIT TILL THE NEXT MORNING TO DO REPAIR AS GATX DID NOT HAVE ALL REQUIRED MATERIAL WITH THEM, AND TO EFFECT REPAIRS DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS WOULD MAKE WORKING CONDITIONS SAFER. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED CAR GATX 44594 HAD NO OUTAGE AND THE REMAINING CARS PRODUCT LEVEL WAS BELOW THE NORMAL LOADING LEVEL.. GATX INITIATED A VACUUM EFFECT AND PRODUCT EQUALIZED IN THE 7 CAR UNIT.  REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED BY 1300 HOURS MARCH 09, AND CARS RELEASED.  MR. JAMISON WAS INFORMED AND ASSURES US MATTER WOULD BE INVESTIGATED TO DETERMINE CAUSE AND TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION IF NECESSARY.

column168: WHILE PREPARING TO LOAD CHECKED BAGGAGE IN MIAMI.  THIS BLACK BAG WAS NOTED LEAKING IN BAGGAGE CART.  LEAKING ITEM IDENTIFIED AS BLACK WOOD SEALER WHICH HAD TOP OF CAN SLIGHTLY OPEN LEAKING CONTENTS OVER THE SIDES OF THE CAN.  NO ADDITIONAL INFORMATION COULD BE READ FROM CAN OR OBTAINED FROM PASSENGER.  ALL OTHER BAGS SEALED, NO DANGEROUS GOODS FOUND.  BLACK SEALER WILL BE CONSIDERED FLAMMABLE THUS REQUIRING THIS REPORT. column168: INBOUND TRAILER #48-4453 WAS BEING UNLOADED BY CONTRACTOR DOCKMAN, NATHAN LAMB.  MR LAMB STATES THAT HE ACCIDENTLY PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH HIS HILO FORK AS HE WAS TRYING TO PICK UP A SKID NEXT TO THE DRUM.  A FORK PUNCTURE WAS MADE TO THE NEXT TO THE DRUM.  A FORK PUNCTURE WAS MADE TO THE LOWER PART OF THE DRUM APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE-DOWN TO STOP THE SPILLAGE AND BAKING SODA WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL TO NEUTRALIZE. LESS THAT 2 GALLONS WERE LOST.  DRUM WILL BE OVER-PACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKING.

03/09/00 AWB BUF 6488478071 FLO, FILE # 2018 F&D, SHIPPER: SCIENCE KIT & BOREAL LAB.  ON 03/08/00 AT 23:31 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN SECONDARY NINE OF D BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC.,146 HUNTER DRIVE, WILIMINGTON, OHIO 48177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN DIANE RAMSDEN AND CAROLYN CORDREY DONNED PROPER PERSONEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND TWO WHITE FIBREBOARD BOXES TAPED TOGETHER WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE BOTTOM BOX.  THEY TESTED THE LIQUID WITH PH PAPER, PH WAS NEUTRAL.  THEY SEPARATED THE BOXES AND OPENED THE LEAKING ONE.  INSIDE THE BOX THEY FOUND TISSUE PAPER AND A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG WHICH WAS HERMATICALLY GOALED CONTAINING A FELINE SPECIMEN IN A CLEAR LIQUID.  ALSO INCLUDED IN THE BOX WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR"EMBALMING FLUID".  THE MSDS  INDICATES THE EMBALMING FLUID TO BE A PHENOL SOLUTION, HAZARD CLASS 5.1, IRRITANT. HAZARDOUS COMPONENTS:  FORMULIN <3.0%, PHENOL 2.75%, ETHYLENE GLYCOL 5.5%.  THEY FOUND A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE PLASTIC BAG CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF THE EMBALMING FLUID.  THEY APPLIED PACKAGING TAPE TO THE PUNCTURE IN THE BAG AND RESEALED THE BOX.  THEY RETAPED THE TWO BOXES BACK TOGETHER, PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS  WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS,  LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE ODOR EMITTING FROM THIS SHIPMENT, WHO WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR.  SHE NEEDED NO ADDITIONAL MEDICAL. CLEAR OF SCENE: 00:28

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  HANDLERS NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE UNIT WHICH APPEARED TO BE A PLASTIC SAMPLE CASE WITH A COMBINATION LOCK.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR THE COMBINATION AND THE UNIT  WAS OPENED.  UPON INSPECTION THERE APPEARED TO BE VARIOUS TYPES OF BEAUTY SUPPLIES.  AMONG THESE SUPPLIES WAS A UNIT WHERE THE ODOR  WAS COMING FROM WHICH CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF FINGERNAIL POLISH.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE CASE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS ATTEMPTED TO THE SOUTHERN REGION OF THE F.A.A. 24 DUTY OFFICE  TO SPECIAL AGENT KEITH HUNTER AT 15:05 (CST) ON 03/24/00.  NOTIFICATION WAS ALSO LEFT VIA VOICEMAIL TO THE F.A.A./MIA/CAFSO AT 15:10 (CST) ALSO ON 03/24/00. PHONE CONTACT WAS ESTABLISHED TO SPECIAL AGENT DIANA LAGUNA/FAA/MIA/CAFSO AT 12:10 (CST) ON 03/27/00.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: ON MARCH 27, 2000 AT 11:55AM OUR ASHLAND DRIVER (TERRY BLAZER) ARRIVED AT PACKERLAND WHEN PRODUCTS, INC, IN LUXEMBURG, WI TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF TWO 300 GALLON POLY TOTES OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 12.5%. THIS CUSTOMER DOES NOT HAVE A DOCK TO UNLOAD, SO YOU MUST UNLOAD DIRECTLY OFF THE BACK OF YOUR TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL, OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PROCEED TO THE GAVELED LOT DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA IN THE REAR OF THE PLANT.  HE WOULD BE MET THERE BY A FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO TAKE THEM OFF.  AT APPROXIMATELY 12:05 PM, OUR DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER, ENTERED THE TRAILER, AND PROCEEDED TO PULL THE FIRST TOTE BACK ABOUT 10 FEET WITH A HAND JACK.  AFTER HE LOWERED THE TOTE DOWN, HE PULLED THE HAND JACK OUT AND WENT TO THE FRONT OF THE TOTE AND JACKED IT BACK UP.  AT THIS POINT HE STARTED TO PUSH THE TOTE TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER HAS A 3 FOOT STEEL PLATE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WHICH IS ABOUT 1/4"  THICK, WHICH REQUIRES YOU TO PUSH THE HAND JACK HARD ENOUGH TO GET THE TOTE AND HAND JACK ON TOP OF THE PLATE.  IT IS AT THIS TIME THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR CAN REACH THE TOTES AND TAKE THEM OFF THE BACK END OF THE TRAILER.  AS HE PUSHED THE TOTE TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, HE FELT THE HAND JACK JUMP ON THE STEEL PLATE, SO HE STOPPED PUSHING AND GRABBED THE RELEASE HANDLE TO LOWER THE TOTE. BEFORE THE HAND JACK DROPPED THE TOTE, THE TWO FRONT WHEELS OF THE HAND JACK DROPPED OFF THE REAR OF THE 3-FOOT STEEL PLATE  CAUSING THE TOTE TO SLIDE OFF THE HAND JACK AND HIT THE GROUND. WHEN THE TOTE HIT THE GROUND IT SPLIT OPEN ON THREE SIDES SPILLING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS ONTO THE GRAVEL LOT.  THE GRAVEL LOT IS TAPERED TO A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA,  WHICH IS APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET FROM THE SPILL.  ALL OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED DRAINED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA, WHICH HAD APPROXIMATELY 7000 GALLONS OF RAINWATER IN IT.  THE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL  RESOURCES (GREEN BAY OFFICE)  WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND AUTHORIZED THE PUMPING OF THE DILUTED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE FROM THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT BASIN TO THE HIGH STRENGTH SPILL TANK.  THIS WAS COMPLETED BY 4:30PM.  THE SPILLED AREA WAS RINSED INTO THE BASIN WITH TAP WATER FOR ABOUT 30 MINUTES. ALL THE WASH DOWN WATER WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE BASIN AND PLACED IN THE HIGH STRENGTH SPILL TANK.

EMPLOYEES WORKING IN THE AREA OF PPGX 1651, DETECTED AN ODOR OF CHLORINE.  THE EMPLOYEES NOTIFIED THE YARD SUPERVISOR WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, CHEMTREC, AND THE CSXT HAZMAT DEPARTMENT.  THE AREA IN AND AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PRIOR TO THE ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND DETERMINED THAT PPGX 1651 WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM APPLIED THE CHLORINE EMERGENCY KIT "C" TO THE LEAKING SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE. THIS ACTION ABATED THE RELEASE OF VAPOR FROM THE CAR.  A TEAM FROM OXYCHEM ALSO INSPECTED THE CAR AND GAUGED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR. THE CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE 183 PSI.  THE CAR HAD BEEN FILLED WITH NITROGEN GAS DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCEDURE.  ONCE THE CAR WAS SECURE ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED BACK TO THE CUSTOMER'S PLANT FOR PURGING AND DEPRESSURIZATION.  AN FRA EXEMPTION (#0003055) WAS GRANTED FOR MOVEMENT OF THE CAR WITH THE "C" KIT IN PLACE.  AT THE PLANT THE REMAINING NITROGEN AND CHLORINE VAPOR WAS PURGED FROM THE CAR.  A TEAM FROM THE SUPPLIER WAS CALLED IN TO SPARGE THE CAR OF ALL VAPOR AND DRAW A VACUUM INSIDE THE CAR.  ONCE THE CAR WAS UNDER VACUUM, THE SRD WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SRD HAD OPENED AND FAILED TO FULLY RESEAT, THUS ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  THE SRD WAS REPAIRED AND RE INSTALLED.

column168: FILE 2022 D. SHIPPER: STATE OF KANSAS, AWB # TOP 1974882024 ELZ. ON 03/22/2000 AT 0228 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT :ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS, ALAN HENDERSON AND MIRANDA SOUTH DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING THE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN INSPECTION. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND IT TO CONTAIN 3 FIBERBOARD BOXES. THEY OPENED EACH OF THESE BOXES AND EACH ONE CONTAINED A 1 QUART GLASS BOTTLE OF GASOLINE. 2 OF THE 3 WERE LEAKING AROUND THE CLOSURES. EACH ONE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES. TOTALING 4 OUNCES IN ALL. THESE BOTTLES DID HAVE TAPE AROUND THE CLOSURES ON THE LIDS, HOWEVER, THE TAPE CAME OFF OF THE TWO THAT LEAKED, CAUSING THE CLOSURES TO BECOME LOOSE. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX AND REPLACED IT INSIDE OF 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED. THERE WAS 1 EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND SHE RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR HER. THERE WERE PROPER MARKINGS, LABELS AND SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT. THIS WAS IN A SPECIFICATION PACKAGE. THE SPEC MARKINGS WERE UN 4G/Y7.5/8/96 USA/+AA0725.

FILE 2022D 03/24/2000, SHIPPER: EVERGREEN PAINTING, AWB# JMO 525811443 ERI. THIS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. 0006 - 03/24/00 A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED ON "A" RAMP ON AIRCRAFT 847AX FLIGHT 381 TOPSIDE IN THE MAIN CARGO AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATORS MICHAEL FRYE, BRUCE CUNNINGHAM AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS RANDY WILLIAMS, TIM HINES AND MIRANDA SOUTH DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE AIRCRAFT. THEY INSPECTED UNIT LOAD DEVICES FOR THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THEY FOUND A WHITE FIBREBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR IN ONE OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE CONTAINERS.THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX, THEY TESTED THE LIQUID, PH READING NEUTRAL. THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING ITEMS: 4 METAL QUART CANS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. EACH METAL CAN HAD A WHITE LABEL MARKED WITH THE CONTENTS OF THE CAN. THE FOLLOWING IS A LIST OF THE CONTENTS OF THOSE METAL CANS: 1- XYLENES, 1- METHYL ALCOHOL, 1- ETHYL ALCOHOL, & 1- ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL. THE METAL CAN MARKED XYLENES LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES DUE TO AN UNSECURE CLOSURE. IN ADDITION TO THE METAL CANS, THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED A 1 QUART PLASTIC CONTAINER WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE SECURED WITH PACKAGING TAPE.  ON THE TOP OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER LID PRINTED IN BLUE MARKER ARE THE WORDS "AMMONIUM NITRATE". THE PLASTIC CONTAINER CONTAINS A WHITE GRANULAR SUBSTANCE. THIS CONTAINER DID NOT LEAK. THERE ARE NO OTHER MARKINGS ON THE METAL CANS OR PLASTIC CONTAINER. ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT IS AN AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATOR WITH CARTRIDGES, COTTON BATTING, LATEX GLOVES, A ROLL OF CLEAR PLASTIC AND AN 8 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "TRITON X" CLEANING SOLUTION. THEY SECURED THE CLOSURE ON THE METAL CAN, REMOVED THE PLASTIC CONTAINER OF AMMONIUM NITRATE RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM. THE AMMONIUM NITRATE WAS REPACKAGED INTO A SEPARATE BOX DUE TO INCOMPATIBILITY OF CHEMICALS. BOTH THE RECOVERY DRUM AND THE BOX CONTAINING THE AMMONIUM NIRATE WERE PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. CLEAR OF SCENE 0028. THERE WERE 6 EMPLOYEES WHO NOTICED THE ODOR EMITTING FROM THIS SHIPMENT, THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR, NO MEDICAL ATTENTION OR FOLLOW UP WAS NEEDED. THEY RETURNED TO THERE NORMAL JOB DUTIES. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED A WORK ODOR WAS INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT AND WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

column168: ON MARCH 24, 2000, MAJESTIC TERMINAL SERVICES (SOUTHWEST AIRLINES CONTRACT CARGO) STATION MANAGER SALLIE LEISTER DISCOVERED A SPILL OF BATTERY ACID IN AIR FREIGHT SHIPMENT CONSIGNED BY PILOT AIR FREIGHT TO SOUTHWEST AIRLINES. THE PACKAGE (1 OF 3 PACKAGES OFFERED IN THE SHIPMENT) CONTAINED AN AUTOMOTIVE TYPE WET CELL BATTERY WITHIN A GOLF TRAINING MACHINE. THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING RETURNED TO PRO INDUSTRIES OF SPOKANE BY PEPPERWOOD PUBLIC GOLF COURSE OF TEMPE, ARIZONA. THE BATTERY WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE CONSIGNEE (PILOT AIR FREIGHT) ARRIVED TO PICK UP THE SHIPMENT. MS. LEISTER NOTICED THE BOX WAS WET AND UPON TRYING TO MOVE THE SHIPMENT, THE BOX FELL APART. SHE REPORTS THAT THE ACID IN THE SHIPMENT DID NOT INJURE HER. UPON DISCOVERY, MS. LEISTER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO LOCAL SOUTHWEST MANAGEMENT AS WELL AS THE SOUTHWEST CARGO SERVICE CENTER IN DALLAS. THE SEA-TAC CASFO WAS THEN NOTIFIED AND SPECIAL AGENT PAT MILLER PERFORMED AN INVESTIGATION.

SHIPPER LOADED TRAILER AT WESTWAY TERMINAL, DRIVER TOOK TRAILER ON HIGHWAY WITHOUT RE-CHECKING THE DOME CLOSURE.  INVESTIGATION FINDS THAT THE FORWARD DOME WAS MOST LIKELY HELD CLOSED FOR THE MAJORITY OF THE TRIP BY VACUUM CAUSED BY WARM PRODUCT INSIDE COLD CONTAINER. AT CONSIGNEE GATE, DRIVER SWUNG WIDE TO LEFT TO ENTER THE GATE, AND STOPPED HARD FOR AUTO COMING OUT OF SIDE STREET.  THE PRODUCT SURGED AND THIS CAUSED THE DOME TO BREAK THE VACUUM SEAL AND A QUANTITY OF PRODUCT ESCAPED AND WAS SPRAYED BY THE WIND BACKWARDS ALONG TRAILER OUTER COVERING, AND ONTO STREET, AND MINOR AMOUNT OF SPRAY REACHED TWO PEDESTRIANS.  (JOSEPH BLAKE, JOHN TERRY).  THE TWO PEDESTRIANS WASHED WITH WATER HAD EYE IRRITATION BUT DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL TREATMENT.  PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM TRAILER ONTO PLANT ROADWAY. PRODUCT INITIALLY CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL OF STONEY CREEK TECHNOLOGIES.  FURTHER NEUTRALIZATION AND REMOVAL BY ENVIRO. CONTRACTOR.  NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE.

CAR WILL CONTINUE TO BE MONITOR WHILE IT IS IN THE YARD AT NORTH PLATTE. IF THE LEAK STARTS WE WILL HAVE TO REPLACE THE GASKET UNDER THE FLANGE. IF NOT THE CAR WILL BE ON ITS WAY. LERCH IMMEDIATELY VENTED THE CAR VIA THE AIR VALVE STOPPED RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THE BASE OF THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE. column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY PACER INTERMODAL REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE EAST YARD. DEVELOPED A DRAYMAN WAS PICKING UP THE CONTAINER WHEN HE NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EASY YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY LOCATED THE 45 FOOT CONTAINER IN THE PARKING AREA RED 218. A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT) WAS NOTED ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THE CHASSIS WHEELS. FIELD TESTING OF THE LIQUID DEVELOPED THE PRODUCT WOULD BURN WHICH WAS CONSISTENT WITH THE PRODUCT LISTED ON THE WAYBILL. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO LOT #6 WHERE IT COULD BE GROUNDED FOR INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS NOTED THE LADING WAS MIXED FREIGHT AND THE DRUMS WERE LOCATED HALF WAY INTO THE CONTAINER. THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF USED PALLETS HELD IN PLACE WITH 2X4'S THAT HAD BEEN PLACED CROSS WAY INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR PROPERLY SECURING HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL. INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS LOCATED ONE AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE WALL THAT WAS EMPTY. UPON REMOVING THE DRUM DEVELOPED THE DRUM HAS A VERY SMALL PIN HOLE IN THE BOTTOM APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH IN FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME. IT APPEARS THE DRUM HAD BEEN SET ON SOMETHING TO CAUSE THE PUNCTURE, HOWEVER INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER FLOORING SHOWED NO DEFECTS WHICH WOULD CAUSE THIS TYPE OF PUNCTURE. IT IS PRESUMED THE DAMAGE WAS DONE PRIOR TO OR DURING LOADING PROCESS. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE FREIGHT RESTOWED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 P.M. (18:00) 3/23/00, A VAN TRAILER (#170) AND TRACTOR (#595) WAS TURNING FROM ROUTE 189 TO US 258 FIVE (5) MILES SOUTH OF FRANKLIN, VA.  WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE PULLED OVER AND FOUND A SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE PORTABLE TANK (IBC) LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY 100-120 GALLONS WERE LOST.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL WERE REMOVED.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED.  EXAMINATION OF THE IBC INDICATED THAT IT HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT THAT HAD GOUGED THE BOTTOM.  IN TRANSIT, A CRACK DEVELOPED.  03/24/00 8:20 AM I RETURNED TO THE SCENE WAS MET BY RAYMOND HERRING, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OFFICER, VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND JIM COVINGTON, ASSISTANT HAZMAT COORDINATOR, SOUTHAMPTON COUNTY OFFICE OF THE SHERIFF.  AFTER REVIEWING THE AREA AND CONSULTING WITH KERITA KEGLE OF DEQ, THEY WERE SATISFIED WITH THE CONDITION OF THE SITE AND SAID THAT NO ADDITIONAL RESPONSE WOULD BE NEEDED. PRELIMINARY EXAMINATION OF THE PORTABLE TANK INDICATES THAT A FORKLIFT HAD PUNCTURED THE OUTER SHELL AND PARTIALLY PENETRATED THE INNER BOTTLE.  THE TANK HAD BEEN RETURNED FROM A CUSTOMER, WASHED, INTERNALLY INSPECTED AND REFILLED.  NO LEAKS OR CRACKS WERE NOTED DURING OR AFTER THE FILLING PROCESS.  A CRACK THEN DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTLE DURING TRANSPORT.  PROPOSED CORRECTIVE ACTION: EXTEND INSPECTION TO ALL TANK BOTTOMS PRIOR TO FILLING.
